The Fight for the Future: A Study of Gen Z’s Activism
Figure 1: Gen Z has been leading every significant movement in recent times
According to Nick Engelfried’s article, Andrea Manning is an African American college
student who was not all that interested in climate change just a couple of years ago. All that she
learned in her Atlanta high school was about polar bears and ice caps, and as a fellow Georgian,
it is easy to understand why that seemed “far from [her] lived reality” and, therefore, nothing for
her to be concerned about. But after helping a friend organize a climate march for Zero House, a
climate change organization, Andrea realized just how much climate change mattered, and not
only in saving the future. She says, “I saw how climate change affects real communities and
racial justice,” and that spurred her to act. Quickly, Andrea became an organizer and pulled off
her first rally in July of 2018, which drew a meager 40 people. But patience and perseverance led
to more fruitful results when she took part in another strike the next year that drew ten times the
size of her original crowd. Andrea is not part of Zero Hour’s executive team and dedicated to
making change.
3
Andrea is just one example out of thousands of how young people today are becoming
more and more involved in various types of activism, not just climate change. This generation of
activists is called Gen Z, and they passionately care about the issues of the world, including
social, racial, and climate justice. That matters because as globalization continues, the world is
going to become more increasingly diverse, and climate issues will continue to worsen without
proper interference. Without this generation being vocal about the rights of others and about
climate change, things will deteriorate, and it will affect not just future generations, but the
current ones as well. However, change has been hard to make. The government is not addressing
the issues that matter to Gen Z swiftly enough, and they are also facing some resistance from
other generation who feel like Gen Z are not united or prepared to create any lasting change.
However, other generations, as well as the government, should be supporting Gen Z’s activism
to make the world a better place.
Background Information on Gen Z
Gen Z is the new, diverse, and most digital generation. They are the generation born
starting roughly from 1996 onwards; however, there is a disagreement about the specific ending
birth year of this group (Dimock). This generation has become the most diverse generation yet
with Mary Meehan, a cultural scientist for 25 years, saying that, according to Census Data, the
United States is already “on its way to becoming a minority majority” country. She gives an
example of how the United States’ Hispanic population “grew at four times the rate of the total
population” between 2000 and 2010. These statistics show just how rapidly diverse the United
States is becoming. If applied to the world as a whole, it is easy to see just how diverse this and
future generations will be. Not only that, but this generation is the most connected since they do
not know a time without computers, phones, and the Internet. Information has always been at
4
their fingertips, and as technology continues to improve, they are going to keep moving along
with it.
Despite their reputation for being selfish technology-obsessed teenagers, Gen Z is
worried about their future and the future of others. They understand that it is the “[color] of their
skin, their sex, their parents’ economic status and their social standing that will determine their
future” (Hertz). This has helped them become more aware of the struggles that other people face,
and it has made them willing to tolerate and empower the voices of those who cannot (Meehan).
This ties directly to their activism, primarily social and racial justice activists. Not only do they
support causes, but they are also keen to make a change
even in the kind of jobs that they have and the businesses
and products that they support. As a study by Fast
Company in 2016 showed, 77% of Gen Z felt that
businesses should include “doing good” as a central aim for
their business, while 45% agreed that they would “rank
working for a company that helps make the world a better place as important as salary”
(Meehan). This shows how conscious Gen Z is of the impact that they make, even with the kinds
of jobs they have. Gen Z is also quick to call out those who are hypocritical and demand justice
for those who are being wronged. All these aspects that categorize this generation are the
foundation that will help them be successful in becoming the change that they want to see.
Figure 2: According to Pew Research Center,
Gen Z sees diversity as good for society
5
Three Issues That Matter to Gen Z
Gen Z cares about a multitude of issues, racial justice being one of the most important to
them. According to Rebecca Bellan’s article for Forbes, Gen Z has recently been at the forefront
of the Black Lives Matter movement that re-erupted last month. She quotes from several youth
leaders, one of whom is Chelsea Miller. She is the co-founder of Freedom March NYC, which
mobilized one of the largest protests to commemorate the anniversary of the burning of Black
Wall Street. Miller says, “[b]eing a young leader in New York, we had to take control of the
narrative because it’s our story. It’s our lives. We have a responsibility to tell it right for the
future generations to come” (qtd. in
Bellan). Miller is not the only one who
thinks it is important for Gen Z to lead
these movements. Nupol Kiazolu, the 19-
year-old president of BLM Greater New
York, addressed a crowd of protestors on
June 7
th
where she said, “[y]oung people
have been carrying every single movement we’ve seen across the world, so it’s time for adults to
step aside and uplift us” (qtd. in Bellan). Both Kiazolu and Miller strongly believe that racial
justice is important and that it is this generation’s responsibility to make a change now instead of
waiting for later. They are not waiting for permission to speak up about the issues that matter to
them. They are taking back the narrative today to ensure that racial justice does happen.
Just as racial justice is very important to Gen Z, gun control is another matter that they
strongly support as a result of massacres and school shootings that have increased in frequency
in the past couple of years. Emma González, a survivor of the Parkland High School shooting,
Figure 3: Gen Z has been at the forefront of the Black Lives Matter
protests
6
has become one of the many faces of the movement. She, along with the other survivors of the
Parkland shooting, helped launch the non-profit organization March For Our Lives, which has
successfully been protesting and marching for gun control ever since. Robbie Martinez, another
activist who successfully organized a walkout at her high school on
March 14
th
and April 20
th
of 2018, said, “I think all of this helped me
realize that we have more power than we think we do” (qtd. in Jenkins
and Lopez). By “we”, Martinez is referring to all the student protestors
who had been working collectively to raise awareness about gun control
issues. Not only that, but other organizations have also realized the
importance of Gen Z’s voice on the matter and have been letting
students take the lead in fighting for gun control. As a young woman
who chose to get involved said, “there was a sense that [the people behind the Women’s March
movement] were looking for students because they wanted students to be the ones organizing
and leading the march” (qtd. Jenkins and Lopez). This means that by having student activists
involved, the Women’s March movement had realized the importance of Gen Z’s support.
Altogether, these protests and initiatives show how involved Gen Z is in gun control matters, and
how important their voices are in creating change. These shootings have had a personal impact
on members of Gen Z, and that has made them more motivated to support the gun control
movement.
Not only is Gen Z vocal about racial justice and gun control, but they are also vocal about
climate change. Andrea Manning, the college student who is now part of Zero Hour’s executive
team, is a great example, but she is not the only one. According to The Guardian, 70,000
schoolchildren hold protests in support of climate change across 270 cities and towns around the
Figure 4: Activists at the
March for Our Lives protest
7
world every week (Nestor). This shows just how motivated, and persistent Gen Z is. Prominent
figures such as Greta Thunberg and Jamie Margolin also make speeches at marches and rallies
urging world leaders to take a decisive stance against
pollution while also inspiring other members of Gen Z to
join in on the movement (Engelfried). Youth leaders are
rallying together and creating organizations dedicated to
informing the public about climate change and how they
can help. As one activist said, “[i]f older generations aren’t
going to be responsible, then in times of crisis youth have to step up and be the adults” (qtd. in
Engelfried). This shows how Gen Z is willing to take charge to make the world a better place. To
Gen Z, climate change is an issue that affects everyone and needs to be dealt with now, instead
of later. By seeing others in their generation speak up about the issues that matter to them, other
members of Gen Z are becoming more empowered to share their voices as well.
How Gen Z Makes Its Voice Heard
To understand just how effective Gen Z’s digital approach to activism is, it is crucial to
see how intimate Gen Z is with the Internet and social media. With the iPhone releasing in 2007,
the oldest members of Gen Z at the time were around ten years old, and they quickly adapted to
technology. Nowadays, most members of Gen Z do not know a time without information at their
fingertips. One study found that the percentage of adolescents who are always online has
increased from 25 to 45 percent between 2015 and 2018 (Boer et al.). This shows just how much
Gen Z is used to technology, and it is easy to see that with all that time spent online, they are
very familiar with using it. Not only are they good at using the Internet, but they are also very
social media savvy. A different study conducted by Palley in 2012 showed that close to 60% of
Figure 5: Students have been missing classes to
raise awareness about climate change
8
Gen Z reported that “social life begins online”, while another 50% felt more comfortable talking
to people online than in real life (Turner). This supports the idea that social media is one of the
common ways in which Gen Z interacts with people online. They also use it to learn about
current events happening around the world as a poll by Business Insider that ran in early 2019
showed that 59% of more than 1,800 surveyed respondents listed social media as a “top news
source” (Taylor). Thanks to always being online and connected through social media, Gen Z has
become intimately familiar with using these forms of technology, which has aided Gen Z in
using them for their activism campaigns.
As a result of their familiarity with social media, Gen Z has been able to use it to further
their activism campaigns and raise awareness about the issues that matter to them. For instance,
Black Lives Matter activists have been using social media to provide information on protests,
explain police shortcuts, and keep the momentum going on the movement (Bellan). In the gun
control movement, many activists use social media to raise
awareness about the importance of the issue. One activist who
was part of the gun control protests said, “I’m going to use
social media to let people know [about pressing issues]” (qtd.
in Jenkins and Lopez). For climate change activists, social
media has helped them launch several strikes and was crucial
in coordinating The Global Climate Strike in 2018 (Engelfried). Social media is so effective in
assisting Gen Z to make their voices heard because it offers them a direct way to communicate
with others without censorship. As Jenkins and Lopez said in their study, “[s]ocial media offers
American youth a ‘no permission necessary’ means of routing around traditional gatekeepers
who limit what can be said”. This means that social media is a way for Gen Z to speak about
Figure 6: Social media has become an
important part of Gen Z's activism.
9
these issues without having the narrative being controlled by others. Not only that, but millions
of people, especially other members of Gen Z, use social media, so a carefully worded and
directed social media campaign can have a more direct impact than other forms of activism.
Social media has the potential to influence the viewer’s opinions on the issue, and being the
generation that intimately knows the best way to utilize it, Gen Z has an edge that helps them
make their voices amplified and heard.
The Morality of Their Methods
Some people argue that Gen Z’s methods of raising awareness are full of deceit and
manipulation, and therefore should not be supported. Molly Roberts, a reporter for The
Washington Post, raised this argument in her article where she discusses the tactics of some
members of Gen Z to ruin President Trump’s recent rally in Tulsa, Oklahoma. She says that
these teens used their social and Internet savvy skills to register for hundreds of thousands of
tickets to Trump’s rally as a prank. Trump, who had been expecting an audience of 1 million,
was greeted by only 6,200 supporters. Roberts argues in her article that this method of deceit and
manipulation is not admirable because it leads to information warfare. She also says that
“celebrating some manipulation and condemning others is an unsustainable tack for anyone who
wants to untangle our world wide web of lies” (Roberts). Add that with Bellan’s article, where
she mentions that Black Lives Matter movement leaders use complicated social media posts to
hide their protest organization activities from the police, and it looks like Gen Z’s methods of
creating change are not that admirable after all.
10
On the contrary, while the methods of some of these activists are not the best, they are
still necessary to prove a point in a society that is quick to dismiss their activism as irrelevant. As
one activist mentioned in Bellan’s article, this society
constantly says that Gen Z is the future, but they also
refuse to step aside and let them lead. Not only that, but
without activism that calls people’s attention and always
remains on the news cycle, people are quick to forget
and move on. Avery Gardiner, the co-president of Brady Campaign, which is a gun-control
organization, pointed out the importance of attention-drawing activism when she said, “[t]he
students were incredibly clever in choosing a date for the march that was about six weeks after
the massacre…[it] forced the news [and] media to keep this in the headlines for about six weeks
and then for a couple of weeks [afterward]” (qtd. in Kanski). By having the march just six weeks
later, those students were able to keep the focus on the message that they were trying to send.
Without doing things that draw attention, Gen Z’s activism will be pointless since no one will be
listening. Even Roberts mentioned at the end of her article that it is “sad that many believe [that]
it’s the [deceitful or manipulative] activism [that is] most likely to succeed in a battlefield
already full of falsehoods, and sadder still that they may be right”. Here, Roberts herself
concedes that without this kind of activism, it is nearly impossible for Gen Z to succeed in
making their voices heard. Gen Z needs to raise awareness about these issues, and in this world,
these usually disapproved of methods are sometimes necessary to make this change happen.
The Effectiveness of Their Methods
As a result of Gen Z’s methods of drawing attention to the causes that they support, they
are able to effectively raise awareness about them, which has the potential to create lasting
Figure 7: If we are the future, act like it
11
change. For example, within seven months, the movement in support of gun control had resulted
in 26 states passing 55 gun laws (Jenkins and Lopez). These are promising results, and with more
time and effort, Gen Z can continue to be the change that they want to see in the world. But it is
not just their campaigning that helps them gain these results. Gen Z is determined and idealistic;
they are not going to be easily stopped by a few setbacks. Gardiner also mentioned this when she
said, “[they] believe that if they speak the truth to power, they will win” (qtd. in Kanski). By this,
Gardiner means that Gen Z believes that by speaking up about these issues, they can create this
change and “win”. Meehan also notes how this generation is a lot more realistic and resourceful
than other generations, which makes them a lot savvier and more stable. All these characteristics
are part of the reason why Gen Z’s methods will be effective in creating change.
In contrast, some argue that Gen Z will be unable to make any lasting change because
they are too divided politically and unmotivated to vote. Kate Taylor, a writer for Business
Insider, argues this point in her article where she mentions that Gen Z is too easily swayed
politically. She uses a testimony by Katy Foster, a 21-year-old college student, who said, “I will
be swayed, honestly, by a two-minute video, which is sad to say” (qtd. in Taylor). Taylor also
quotes from another member of Gen Z who says that “there is a pretty big political divide” (qtd.
in Taylor). Another perspective notes that Gen Z does not have the passion or desire to vote.
According to a political science professor that Taylor also quoted from, there is a misplaced hope
that Gen Z will be the generation to “fix problems” and “change the nature and dynamics of
politics” (qtd. in Taylor). This shows that Taylor believes that the hope that many place in Gen Z
to fix society’s issues is misplaced. Based on this, Taylor is arguing that political disunity and an
unwillingness to vote will prevent Gen Z from creating any lasting change.
12
On the contrary, Gen Z does not need to be united politically to create this change. They
are already united on the issues that matter to them. That will enable them, along with their
effective social media campaigns and passion for doing what is right, to create change even if
they do not agree politically. One person who believes that they will be able to create this change
is Michele Nestor. Nestor is a waste management
specialist who discussed Gen Z’s activism when it comes
to climate change. In her article, Nestor says that despite
their unwillingness to vote and their division politically,
she still has hope in them because they aim to have a
personal impact through their work. She thinks that they
have a “longer-term view of their employment
relationship[,]” which is encouraging “because change must come from within an organization”
(Nestor). This means that Gen Z is patient and willing to put in the effort to see their activism
pay off, which will help them create change. So, despite their political division, their methods
will still be effective in assisting them to become the change they want to see in the world.
Why Other Generations and the Government Should Care
All of Gen Z’s efforts are grand and noble, but how does this affect other generations?
Why should these other generations and the government
care? It is important to see that despite Gen Z fighting for
their future, and the future of those after them, it is still
primarily previous generations and the government who
should be caring about and striving to fix these problems.
These problems are not the fault of Gen Z, yet they have
Figure 8: Gen Z may be divided when it comes
to politics, but they aren't divided on the causes
that matter to them
Figure 9: Gen Z has the potential to make the
world a better place.
13
taken it upon themselves to act since the government is not responding. Some people from
previous generations have been trying to create change, but things are still not moving or
changing as fast as they should be. This stalemate can result in severe repercussions for future
generations, which is why everyone should be supporting and uplifting Gen Z’s voices today.
Inaction, empty promises, or worse, trying to hinder Gen Z’s activism can make their already
dismal future a worse place because some of these issues, especially climate change, need to be
dealt with now and today. With Gen Z’s technology and social media connectivity, their
tolerance, their support of those who have been wronged, and their passion for doing what is
right, Gen Z is going to become the change that they want to see in this world. It is up to other
generations and to the government to aid them in making the world a better place.

i
Choosing a Topic
The process of writing this research-based argument was a wonderful learning opportunity, as
well as a test. I have only written a research paper a couple of times, and those papers did not
have as many sources as I had for this paper, nor were they as long.
I first chose this topic because of the article that I analyzed in the first unit of this course. At that
time, I wasn’t sure what my final argument would be, but the issues of Gen Z mattered to me
more than the rest of the article choices because I am a part of Gen Z.
After analyzing that article, which covered a multitude of issues that Gen Z faces as well as what
they value, I chose a narrowed topic to research for the second unit of this course. I was curious
about why Gen Z was such an activist generation and my research led me to finally choosing my
final topic for this essay.
I decided to discuss some of the causes that Gen Z supports, why they care about them, how they
raise awareness or make their voices heard, and then argue why it is important for other
generations as well as the government to support them.
The Process
The process of researching for this essay was a little difficult. There were first issues with the
library, and then I couldn’t find a lot of primary sources that I could use for my argument. I tried
searching with different keywords but I didn’t really find a scientific study or other strong
primary source that directly discussed Gen Z’s activism.
15
I had a much easier time finding articles and secondary sources, and they do make up the bulk of
my research. However, I tried to choose articles that had a good ethos either by who the author
is, or by the way the author presents their argument.
Rhetorical Appeals
I used mostly logos, in the form of examples and statistics, and ethos, in the form of quotations
from credible people, to argue my point. For instance, I quoted from Mary Meehan, who has
been a cultural scientist for 25 years. By quoting from her, I was using an appeal to ethos
because she has a strong credibility that supports the point I was trying to make. An example of
an appeal to logos was when I mentioned that 70,000 children protested in support of climate
change in 270 cities and towns every week. Both these examples and the other ones that I used in
my paper helped to reinforce my points.
Peer Review & Revision
Having the Smarthinking tutor’s feedback helped me revise my paper more effectively. I like
having others review my work so that I can get an outside opinion. I think it’s a great way to find
flaws in my argument, because it might sound logical to me, but there may have been something
I overlooked which someone else could catch. It also makes the writing process easier because I
then have specific things to fix or change. The tutor’s response gave me all of that and served as
a guide as I revised my essay.
My Failures and Successes
16
I’m most proud of myself for actually finishing this essay. At the start of the semester, I was a
little overwhelmed at the thought of having over 8 sources and 3000+ words for one paper. But
here I am with 12 sources and a total of over 5000 words.
One of the things that I could have improved on was explaining the evidence that I used. I
thought I had explained the evidence satisfactorily, but from the feedback I received, I realized
that I still need to rewrite my explanations so that they are much clearer. For instance, I used two
quotes in my first paragraph under Three Issues That Matter to Gen Z and I didn’t fully explain
how these quotes related to my point. During my revision, I tried to fix this issue in all my
paragraphs by using a sentence to explain each quote and statistic, no matter how obvious it
seemed.
What This Course Has Taught Me
This course has taught me to not be afraid of “over-achieving”. I’ve been told that, at times, I
always go above and beyond what is required especially when I don’t have to, and that is shown
a lot through my essays. I always struggled with writing essays that didn’t overly exceed the
word count. For instance, in my first essay for ENGL 1101, I wrote over 1,100 words forgetting
that the word count was only 800-900. I submitted it, but then a few days later, I seriously
panicked when I realized that the word count suggested 800-900 words. I was terrified that it
would affect my grade, but it didn’t. I didn’t fully realize what that meant at the time, but after
writing the essays for this course, I understood that I shouldn’t have panicked so much about
going over the suggested word count because it’s just a guide.
Another key thing that this course has taught me, that I will continue to use, is how to persuade
someone, especially when I personally don’t have any experience or ethos in the subject. Now, if
17
someone says, “you haven’t personally experienced XYZ, how can you say that?” I know how to
argue my point using effective research so that I can eventually say, “no, I don’t have a personal
experience, but my research does make me a credible authority on the subject”.
Overall, this course has taught me a lot about myself as a writer, and it has helped me hone my
skills in persuasive writing. Hopefully, I will continue to use these skills in the future.
